  "insights": {
    "title": "Insights on Children Aged 12 to 23 Months - PCV Vaccinations",
    "subtitle": "Key patterns in PCV dose progression by region and background characteristics.",
    "overview": "PCV coverage improved nationally from 2022 to 2025, but completion from first to third dose remains the central gap. Nationally, PCV 1 rose from 81.8 to 90.9, PCV 2 from 78.0 to 85.1, and PCV 3 from 71.5 to 77.7. The strongest concern is not first-dose reach, but maintaining coverage through PCV 3, especially in lower-performing regions and among children without visible vaccination cards.",
    "sections": [
      {
        "heading": "National gains are clear, but dropout across doses persists",
        "body": "The 2025 profile shows high first-dose contact but lower third-dose completion. PCV 1 is 90.9, PCV 2 is 85.1, and PCV 3 is 77.7. This taper from dose 1 to dose 3 remains substantial even after year-to-year gains, indicating that follow-through is the key challenge."
      },
      {
        "heading": "Regional divide is wide for PCV 3",
        "body": "Regional spread in 2025 is large, especially for completion. PCV 3 ranges from 97.1 in Ilocos Region to 21.2 in BARMM, with Zamboanga Peninsula also low at 62.3 and several regions clustered around the high 60s. High first-dose coverage does not guarantee equally high third-dose completion across regions."
      },
      {
        "heading": "Regional change from 2022 to 2025 is mixed",
        "body": "Some regions posted strong PCV 3 gains, including Davao Region, SOCCSKSARGEN, and MIMAROPA. Others declined, including CAR, Zamboanga Peninsula, and Central Visayas. The national improvement therefore combines large advances in some places with slippage in others."
      },
      {
        "heading": "Vaccination-card status sharply separates outcomes",
        "body": "Children with cards seen have very high 2025 coverage (97.6 for PCV 1 and 91.7 for PCV 3). Coverage drops for children with cards not seen (83.3 for PCV 1, 50.3 for PCV 3), and falls further for children who never had a card (40.0 for PCV 1, 25.0 for PCV 3). This is one of the strongest structural divides in the page."
      },
      {
        "heading": "Birth order and socioeconomic gradients reinforce completion gaps",
        "body": "Later birth orders and lower socioeconomic groups consistently show weaker coverage. For birth order 6+, PCV 3 is 64.8 compared with 83.0 for first births. By wealth, PCV 3 ranges from 68.5 in the lowest quintile to 87.0 in the highest, and education shows a similar gradient from lower schooling to postsecondary/college levels."
      }
    ],
    "takeaways": [
      "PCV coverage improved nationally from 2022 to 2025, but the largest gap remains completion from first to third dose.",
      "Regional inequality in PCV 3 is substantial, with very high completion in some regions and low completion in BARMM and parts of Mindanao/Visayas.",
      "Children without visible vaccination cards, higher birth-order children, and poorer households are much more likely to miss PCV dose completion."
    ]
  },
  "subtitle": "Percentage of children aged 12 to 23 months who received PCV doses according to background characteristics: Philippines, 2022 and 2025"
}
